' Runtime test for bug-374: a user-declared `RESOURCE T CLOSE BY nativeOp` is
' closed by lexical drop when its binding leaves scope, on EVERY exit path.
'
' Before the fix, `resource_cleanup_symbol` resolved a close op only through
' `builtins::resource_close_function` — an 8-entry table of the language's own
' resources (File/Socket/Listener/...). A `RESOURCE Db CLOSE BY sql::close` was
' not in it, so the bind site's `else if let Some(symbol)` fell through, no
' `ActiveCleanup::Resource` was registered, and scope exit emitted NEITHER the
' close NOR the record reclaim. No diagnostic, exit 0, correct output — and a
' leaked sqlite3 handle plus its 80-byte record on every drop.
'
' The spec (`./mfb spec language resource-management` §15) states the guarantee
' this pins, and uses a *native* resource as its own worked example:
'
'   Resources are closed automatically by lexical drop (§14.7) when their owning
'   binding leaves scope, on every exit path: normal scope exit, RETURN,
'   EXIT/CONTINUE, FAIL, PROPAGATE, an auto-propagated failure, and TRAP routing.
'
' WHY THIS FIXTURE IS SHAPED AS A HOT LOOP. A leak is invisible to exit status —
' that is precisely why the bug survived 18 native fixtures, every one of which
' closes explicitly and so never exercised drop at all. Retention is the signal,
' so each path runs enough iterations that a per-iteration leak is unmistakable:
' measured on macOS aarch64, this program peaked at 5.84 GB before the fix and
' 18 MB after (308x). A golden `.run` cannot assert RSS, so the loop count is
' what converts the leak into an observable — a crash or an OOM rather than a
' quietly-passing exit 0. Do NOT "tidy" this by lowering the iteration counts or
' by adding explicit closes: an explicit close is exactly what hid the bug.
IMPORT io

RESOURCE Db CLOSE BY sql::close

LINK "sqlite3" AS sql
  FUNC open(path AS String) AS RES Db
    SYMBOL "sqlite3_open"
    ABI (path CString, db OUT CPtr) AS status CInt32
    RETURN db
    SUCCESS_ON status = 0
  END FUNC
  FUNC close(RES db AS Db) AS Nothing
    SYMBOL "sqlite3_close"
    ABI (db CPtr) AS status CInt32
    SUCCESS_ON status = 0
  END FUNC
END LINK

' §15's "normal scope exit": the reproduction from the bug report, verbatim in
' shape — open, then fall off the end of the function without closing.
FUNC dropNormal() AS Nothing
  RES db AS Db = sql::open(":memory:")
END FUNC

' §15's "RETURN": an early RETURN past the end of the function must run the same
' cleanup the fall-through path does. Two exit paths, two close sites.
FUNC dropReturn(n AS Integer) AS Integer
  RES db AS Db = sql::open(":memory:")
  IF n > 0 THEN
    RETURN 1
  END IF
  RETURN 0
END FUNC

' §15's "EXIT": the binding is inside the loop BODY, so it is a fresh resource
' per iteration and the `EXIT WHILE` leaves the scope holding a live one.
FUNC dropExit() AS Nothing
  MUT i AS Integer = 0
  WHILE i < 3
    RES db AS Db = sql::open(":memory:")
    IF i = 1 THEN
      EXIT WHILE
    END IF
    i = i + 1
  END WHILE
END FUNC

' §15's "CONTINUE": the same per-iteration binding, left via the back edge
' rather than the loop's normal end.
FUNC dropContinue() AS Nothing
  MUT i AS Integer = 0
  WHILE i < 3
    RES db AS Db = sql::open(":memory:")
    i = i + 1
    CONTINUE WHILE
  END WHILE
END FUNC

' §15's "FAIL" + "TRAP routing": the failure unwinds out of a scope holding a
' live resource, and the close must happen on the way out — not be skipped
' because the scope is leaving abnormally.
FUNC dropFail() AS Nothing
  RES db AS Db = sql::open(":memory:")
  FAIL error(77050002, "intentional failure to reach the drop path")
END FUNC

FUNC driveFail() AS Nothing
  dropFail()
  RETURN NOTHING
  TRAP(err)
    IF err.code <> 77050002 THEN FAIL err
    RETURN NOTHING
  END TRAP
END FUNC

' A resource that IS closed explicitly must not then be closed a second time by
' scope exit. Since plan-59-B the `closed` flag makes the second close a defined
' no-op (`ERR_RESOURCE_CLOSED`, benign on the drop path), which is what makes
' this fix safe for the 18 existing fixtures that all close explicitly. This
' drives that close-exactly-once path in the same binary as the drop paths.
FUNC closeExplicitly() AS Nothing
  RES db AS Db = sql::open(":memory:")
  sql::close(db)
END FUNC

FUNC main() AS Integer
  MUT i AS Integer = 0
  WHILE i < 2000
    dropNormal()
    LET r = dropReturn(1)
    dropExit()
    dropContinue()
    driveFail()
    closeExplicitly()
    i = i + 1
  END WHILE
  io::print("drops=" & toString(i))
  io::print("done")
  RETURN 0
END FUNC
